        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.0,
                "text": "Monitoring and dose adjustments"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 46
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Refer to Table 2 for the timing of the first level."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 47
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Bloods for vancomycin levels should be taken at the scheduled time immediately before the next dose is due."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 48
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Take a single venous sample (specimen container: Vacutainer SST 367354 yellow top)."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 49
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Continue vancomycin administration after blood has been taken."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 50
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Do NOT await level result before giving the next dose unless:"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 51
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "A) Patient is renally impaired;"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 52
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "B) The previous level was high."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 53
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Peak levels are NOT required, unless recommended by a microbiologist;"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 54
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "The pre-dose serum level should be between 10-20 mg/litre;"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 55
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Expected target range in mild-moderate infection: 10-15mg/l;"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 56
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Expected target range in endocarditis, staph aureus, severe and any other deep seated infections: 15-20mg/l;"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 57
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Check the results, review and adjust subsequent doses, according to Table 3 if the serum level is outside of the reference range."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 58
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.1,
                "text": "Table3:  TARGET LEVEL and DOSE ADJUSTMENT"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 59
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "sequence_num": 60,
            "data": {
                "num_rows": 4,
                "num_cols": 2,
                "table_items": [
                    {
                        "text": "Pre-dose level <10mg/l"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Check to ensure that previous dose(s) have been given as prescribed and no missed doses. If the levels appear genuine, consider increasing the dose and/or frequency. Increase dose step wise by 500mg, up to a maximum of 1.5g bd. Repeat level in 24hrs."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Pre-dose level 10-20mg/L"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Continue dose and monitoring as above."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "In deep seated infections, if trough >10mg/L but <15mg/L"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Check to ensure that previous dose(s) have been given as prescribed and no missed doses. If the levels appear genuine, consider increasing the dose and/or frequency. Increase dose step wise by 500mg, up to a maximum of 1.5g bd. Repeat level in 24hrs."
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Pre-dose level >20mg/L"
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Check when the assay was taken in relation to the vancomycin dose - high levels can result from samples being taken too soon after the infusion. Check where blood sample was taken from \u2013 false high levels can be obtained from samples taken from the same line that the drug was infused through. Check patient's renal function. Increase in levels may be related to a decreased creatinine clearance. If level appears genuinely high, withhold the dose, and repeat the level until it is in normal range. Then widen the dosing interval from 12hrly to 24 hrly, or reduce the dose stepwise by 250mg-500mg daily, repeat level after 24hrs."
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
